          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "H4"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_2",
          "href": null,
          "name": "2696",
          "text": "Daniel Wahl has had an important insight that makes this book an essential read for anyone trying to change the world. The necessary catalyst is in the title of this book: “regenerative systems.”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_3",
          "href": null,
          "name": "f3a1",
          "text": "Thank you Albert!",
          "metadata": {
            "id": "1*dSOqTGaUtNQQ_gjSO1dqDw.tiff",
            "alt": null
          },
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": "INSET_CENTER",
          "markups": [],
          "type": "IMG"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_4",
          "href": null,
          "name": "87bf",
          "text": "To quote Wahl, “Sustainability is not a fixed state to reach and then maintain, it is a community-based learning process aimed at increasing the health and resilience of our communities, our bioregional economies, ecosystems, and of the planetary life-support system as a whole.”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_5",
          "href": null,
          "name": "a44b",
          "text": "This is the core realization of Rob Hopkins (Transition Handbook) and David Fleming (Lean Logic) as well, but Wahl’s book gets to the assembly language programming, explaining how ecological literacy and the social, technological, and entrepreneurial skills required for the transition are the entry point that leads to everything else. Arguably ecological literacy is already the foundation of much that is new in the world of industrial design — it is called biomimicry.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_6",
          "href": null,
          "name": "e188",
          "text": "Biological and ecological design intelligence is starting to reinvent the way we design communities, businesses, cities, and industries. This book gets out in front of that with the larger picture. We need to do these things, now, or we may not be here in another century.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_7",
          "href": null,
          "name": "f99c",
          "text": "Wahl says, “We need to dare to envision a sustainable world, by re-designing our food systems, transport systems, energy systems, economic systems, and education systems, but most of all, we need to re-envision how we collaborate and how we relate to each other and the natural world.”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_8",
          "href": null,
          "name": "8e68",
          "text": "Whether we have time to make this unprecedented change in our social contract is still in doubt. Set your doubts aside for the moment and let this book give you a sense of “… but what if?”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_9",
          "href": null,
          "name": "27d1",
          "text": "If we are going to get this right, it will begin here.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "6d396a20154b_10",
          "href": null,
          "name": "dd1b",
          "text": "[My friend and wise elder of the ecovillage and the permaculture movement Albert Bates kindly wrote this review of Designing Regenerative Cultures on Amazon. I copied it here to be able to share it more widely without advertising the big whole seller, an editor and author friendly alternative to amazon in the USA is the ISBS.]",
